Supplementary
	Applications etc
		Regulations may make provision as to the making and determination of anyapplication for the amendment of a register of common land or town or villagegreens under or for the purposes of this Part.
		Regulations under subsection (1) may in particular make provision as to—
			the steps to be taken by a person before making an application;
			the form of an application;
			the information or evidence to be supplied with an application;
			the fee payable on an application (which may be a fee determined by theperson to whom the application is made);
			the persons to be notified of an application;
			the publication of an application;
			the making of objections to an application;
			the persons who must be consulted, or whose advice must be sought, inrelation to an application;
			the holding of an inquiry before determination of an application;
			the evidence to be taken into account in making a determination and theweight to be given to any evidence;
			the persons to be notified of any determination;
			the publication of a determination;
			the amendments to be made by a commons registration authority to a registerof common land or town or village greens pursuant to a determination;
			the time at which any such amendments are to be regarded as having beenmade.
		In the case of an application made for the purposes of any of—
			sections 6 to 8, 12 and 13,
			paragraph 1 or 3 of Schedule 1,
			paragraph 2 or 3 of Schedule 2, and
			paragraph 2(5)(a) of Schedule 3,
				regulations under subsection (1) may make provision as to the persons entitledto make the application.
		An application made for the purposes of any of—
			sections 6, 7, 10, 11, 12, 13 and 15, and
			paragraph 1 or 3 of Schedule 1,
			shall, subject to any provision made by or under this Part, be granted.
		Regulations under subsection (1) may include provision for the appropriatenational authority to appoint a person to discharge any or all of itsfunctions in relation to an application made to it under section 16.
		Regulations may make provision as to the making and determination of anyproposal by a commons registration authority to amend a register on its owninitiative pursuant to section 19, Schedule 2 or paragraph 2(5)(b) of Schedule3.
		Regulations under subsection (6) may in particular make provision as to—
			the persons to be notified of a proposal;
			the publication of a proposal (and the information or evidence to bepublished with a proposal);
			the making of objections to a proposal;
			the persons who must be consulted, or whose advice must be sought, inrelation to a proposal;
			the holding of an inquiry before determination of a proposal;
			the evidence to be taken into account in making a determination and theweight to be given to any evidence;
			the persons to be notified of any determination;
			the publication of a determination;
			the amendments to be made by a commons registration authority to a registerof common land or town or village greens pursuant to a determination.
		Regulations under this section may include provision for—
			the appropriate national authority to appoint persons as eligible todischarge functions of a commons registration authority in relation toapplications made to, or proposals made by, the commons registrationauthority; and
			the appointment of one or more of those persons to discharge functions ofthe commons registration authority in the case of any description ofapplication or proposal.
		Regulations under this section may provide for the Church Commissioners toact with respect to any land or rights belonging to an ecclesiastical beneficeof the Church of England which is vacant.
	Electronic registers
		Regulations may require or permit the whole or any part of a register keptunder this Part to be kept in electronic form.
		Regulations under subsection (1) may include provision as to—
			requirements to be complied with in relation to the recording ofinformation in electronic form;
			the certification of information recorded in electronic form (including thestatus of print-outs of such information).
		Regulations under subsection (1) may also include provision as to theprocess of converting a register, or part of a register, into electronic form.
		The provision referred to in subsection (3) includes in particularprovision—
			as to the publicity to be given to such a conversion;
			requiring a provisional electronic version to be made available forinspection and comment;
			as to the holding of an inquiry in relation to any question arising as aresult of the conversion.

Status and constitution of commons councils
	Status 
		A commons council is not to be regarded as the servant or agent of theCrown or as enjoying any status, immunity or privilege of the Crown.
		The property of a commons council is not to be regarded as the property of,or as property held on behalf of, the Crown.
		A commons council is not to be regarded as an authority to which section28G of the Wildlife and Countryside Act [1981 (c.69)](/id/ukpga/1981/69?view=plain "Go to item of legislation") applies.
	Constitution 
		The appropriate national authority must by regulations prescribe standardterms as to the constitution and administration of commons councils (in thisPart, the “standard constitution”).
		The terms of the standard constitution apply to every commons council,subject as follows.
		An order under section 26 may also make provision as to the constitutionand administration of a commons council.
		Provision which may be made under subsection (3) includes in particular—
			provision supplementary to any term of the standard constitution;
			provision disapplying any such term;
			provision replacing any such term.
		Where in relation to a commons council—
			provision is made under subsection (3) that is inconsistent with any termof the standard constitution, and
			any such term has not been expressly disapplied under that subsection,
				the provision made under subsection (3) prevails, to the extent of theinconsistency, over the term of the standard constitution.
		Terms of the standard constitution prescribed by regulations undersubsection (1) may be amended by further regulations under that subsection;and this section applies in relation to such terms as amended as it applies inrelation to the terms as first prescribed.
	Constitution: supplementary
		This section applies in relation to terms as to the constitution andadministration of a commons council contained in—
			the standard constitution; or
			an order under section 26.
		The terms may in particular include terms as to—
			the membership of the council;
			participation in the council by persons other than members;
			the proceedings of the council;
			the keeping and publication of accounts, annual reports and otherinformation relating to the council.
		The terms referred to in subsection (2)(a) include in particular terms asto—
			the appointment of members (by election or otherwise);
			the term for which members are appointed;
			co-option of members;
			the conduct of members;
			resignation and disqualification of members;
			termination and renewal of membership;
			payment of allowances to members.
		The terms referred to in subsection (2)(b) include in particular terms asto—
			entitlement to elect members;
			entitlement to attend meetings.
		The terms referred to in subsection (2)(c) include in particular terms asto—
			the frequency of meetings;
			voting procedures at meetings;
			committees and sub-committees.
		The terms referred to in subsection (2)(d) include in particular terms asto—
			the appointment of auditors;
			the preparation and publication of accounts;
			the preparation and publication of annual reports.
		Subject to any terms made of the kind referred to in subsection (2)(c), acommons council may regulate its own proceedings.

Commons councils: supplementary
	Consequential provision
		The appropriate national authority may by order under section 26 make anyprovision specified in subsection (2) if it appears to the authority desirableto do so in consequence of functions conferred on a commons council inrelation to any land.
		The provision referred to in subsection (1) is provision to—
			vary or abolish the jurisdiction so far as relating to the land of anycourt of a description referred to in Part 1 of Schedule 4 to theAdministration of Justice Act [1977 (c. 38)](/id/ukpga/1977/38?view=plain "Goto item of legislation") (certain ancient courts);
			vary or revoke any regulations or arrangement made under the Commons Act[1908 (c. 44)](/id/ukpga/1908/44?view=plain "Go to item of legislation");
			vary or revoke any scheme made under the Commons Act [1899 (c.30)](/id/ukpga/1899/30?view=plain "Go to item of legislation"), or anyarrangement arising under such a scheme;
			vary or revoke any Act made under the Commons Act [1876 (c.56)](/id/ukpga/1876/56?view=plain "Go to item of legislation") confirming aprovisional order of the Inclosure Commissioners or any arrangement arisingunder such an Act;
			vary or revoke any local or personal Act, or any scheme or arrangementunder such an Act, which relates to the management or maintenance of, or theexercise of rights of common over, the land.
		The appropriate national authority may not under subsection (1) makeprovision specified in subsection (2)(c) to (e) to the extent that to do sowould have the effect of abolishing or restricting a right of access ofwhatever nature exercisable by members of the public generally or by anysection of the public.
	Variation and revocation of establishment orders
		The appropriate national authority may by order under section 26 revoke aprevious order under that section establishing a commons council only if it issatisfied that—
			the council has ceased to operate;
			the council is failing to discharge its functions in an effective manner;or
			the council is, in discharging its functions, failing to have sufficientregard to the public interest as required by section 31.
		An order under section 26 revoking a previous order under that section mayinclude—
			provision for the transfer of rights, property and liabilities of thecommons council;
			provision amending any enactment previously amended under section 36 inrelation to the council.
		Section 27 applies to an order under section 26 varying or revoking aprevious order under that section as it applies to an order under that sectionestablishing a commons council (but as if the references in section 27 to landspecified in the order were to land affected by the variation or revocation).
